rather than try to remember what version or some strange build config
I think it makes more sense to commit a Vagrant file
For deterministic builds there is Gitian too. Specifically made for this purpose
I use Vagrant because then other people on my team can just clone the lib and have it locally setup

> This performs a build inside a VM, with deterministic inputs and outputs. If the build script takes care of all sources of non-determinism (mostly caused by timestamps), the result will always be the same. This allows multiple independent verifiers to sign a binary with the assurance that it really came from the source they reviewed.

build systems, compilers, linkers and stuff do not always produce deterministic output. Mostly that happens when timestamps are part of the process. you can use something like faketime to et an arbitrary time to make it deterministic :wink:
`FAKETIME_PROGS="ar ranlib date dmg genisoimage“` < those would introduce non-determinism for example
I’ll be sure to try it out

Depending on what you build with it, you’ll need lots of hacks to get determinism, but after that first setup is done it’s pretty cool, cause you build with one command. Many crypto currencies use it because Bitcoin does :smile:
So I had my fights with it before :smile:
